SIMPLE: favor
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: favor
<hw>fa"vor</hw> <pr>(f⟦amac⟧"v⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written
also <ets>favour</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[OF. <ets>favor</ets>, F.
<ets>faveur</ets>, L. <ets>favor</ets>, fr. <ets>favere</ets> to be
favorable, cf. Skr. <ets>bh⟦amac⟧vaya</ets> to further, foster,
causative of <ets>bh⟦umac⟧</ets> to become, be. Cf. <er>Be</er>. In the
phrase <ets>to curry favor</ets>, <ets>favor</ets> is prob. for
<ets>favel</ets> a horse. See 2d <er>Favel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Kind regard; propitious aspect; countenance; friendly disposition;
kindness; good will.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hath crawled into the <qex>favor</qex> of the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of countenancing, or the condition of being
countenanced, or regarded propitiously; support; promotion;
befriending.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But found no <qex>favor</qex> in his lady's eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Jesus increased in wisdom and stature, and in <qex>favor</qex>
with God and man.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ii. 52.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind act or office; kindness done or granted;
benevolence shown by word or deed; an act of grace or good will, as
distinct from justice or remuneration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beg one <qex>favor</qex> at thy gracious hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mildness or mitigation of punishment;
lenity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could not discover the lenity and <qex>favor</qex> of this
sentence.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The object of regard; person or thing
favored.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All these his wondrous works, but chiefly man,⟦br⟧
His chief delight and <qex>favor</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A gift or present; something bestowed as an evidence
of good will; a token of love; a knot of ribbons; something worn as a
token of affection; <as>as, a marriage <ex>favor</ex> is a bunch or knot
of white ribbons or white flowers worn at a wedding</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wear thou this <qex>favor</qex> for me, and stick it in thy
cap.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Appearance; look; countenance; face.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This boy is fair, of female <qex>favor</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Partiality; bias.</def>
<rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A letter or epistle; -- so called in civility or
compliment; <as>as, your <ex>favor</ex> of yesterday is
received</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Love locks.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Challenge to the favor</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Challenge for favor</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>the
challenge of a juror on grounds not sufficient to constitute a principal
challenge, but sufficient to give rise to a probable suspicion of favor
or bias, such as acquaintance, business relation, etc. See
<cref>Principal challenge</cref>, under <er>Challenge</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>In favor of</b></col>, <cd>upon the side of; favorable to; for
the advantage of.</cd> -- <col><b>In favor with</b></col>, <cd>favored,
countenanced, or encouraged by.</cd> -- <col><b>To curry favor</b></col>
<ety>[see the etymology of <er>Favor</er>, above]</ety>, <cd>to seek to
gain favor by flattery, caresses, kindness, or officious
civilities.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>With one's favor</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>By one's favor</b></col></mcol>, <cd>with leave; by
kind permission.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But, <qex>with your favor</qex>, I will treat it here.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Kindness; countenance; patronage; support;
lenity; grace; gift; present; benefit.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Favor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Favor
<hw>Fa"vor</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Favored</conjf> <pr>(f⟦amac⟧"v⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Favoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Written also
<ets>favour</ets>.]</ety> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>favorer</ets>,
<ets>favorir</ets>. See <er>Favor</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To regard with kindness; to support; to aid, or to have the
disposition to aid, or to wish success to; to be propitious to; to treat
with consideration or tenderness; to show partiality or unfair bias
towards.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O happy youth! and <qex>favored</qex> of the skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>favoreth</qex> Joab, . . . let him go after Joab.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Sam. xx. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The painter] has <qex>favored</qex> her squint admirably.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To afford advantages for success to; to facilitate;
<as>as, a weak place <ex>favored</ex> the entrance of the
enemy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To resemble in features; to have the aspect or looks
of; <as>as, the child <ex>favors</ex> his father</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The porter owned that the gentleman <qex>favored</qex> his
master.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Favorable</ent>⟦br⟧
